In article <KAPLAN.94Jul28130944@bogtown.watson.ibm.com>, kaplan@watson.ibm.com 
(Marc A. Kaplan) writes:

>  One of our local cellular carriers has started advertising digital
> service with full page ads in the New York Times claiming that they
> will keep your conversations "secret".  What, if any, are the
> technical bases for these claims?

In Europe, the basis is a stream cipher called A5. This takes 2^40 effort to
break, so it will protect you against casual eavesdroppers. For details of
the algorithm, see my post of 17 Jun 1994 13:43:28 GMT with message id
<2ts9a0$95r@lyra.csx.cam.ac.uk>,

Ross
